Socket.Name: Units
Socket.Label: Units
Socket.Hint: Unit for expression of treshold and actual value.

BoxLocalization.Label: Founded Implication
BoxLocalization.Hint: a/(a+b) >= p ... at least 100*p [%] of objects satisfying A satisfy also S

BoxLocalization.Label: Critical Implication
BoxLocalization.Hint: The binomical test does not reject on the level alpha the null hypothesis P(S|A)<=p in favour of alternative P(S|A)>p

BoxLocalization.Label: Above Average Implication
BoxLocalization.Hint: Among objects satisfying A there are at least 100*p [%] more objects satisfying S than there are objects satisfying S in the whole data matrix.

BoxLocalization.Label: Below Average Implication
BoxLocalization.Hint: Among objects satisfying A there are at least 100*p [%] less objects satisfying S than there are objects satisfying S in the whole data matrix.

BoxLocalization.Label: Double Founded Implication
BoxLocalization.Hint: a/(a+b+c) >= p ... at least 100*p [%] of objects satisfying A or S satisfy both A and S

BoxLocalization.Label: Double Critical Implication
BoxLocalization.Hint: The binomical test does not reject on the level alpha the null hypothesis P(AandS|AorS)<=p in favour of alternative P(AandS|AorS)>p

BoxLocalization.Label: Founded Equivalence
BoxLocalization.Hint: (a+d)/n >= p ... at least 100*p [%] objects have the same truth value for A and S.

BoxLocalization.Label: Critical Equivalence
BoxLocalization.Hint: The binomical test does not reject on the level alpha the null hypothesis P(A and S have the same truth value)<=p in favour of alternative P(A and S have the same truth value)>p

BoxLocalization.Label: Simple Deviation
BoxLocalization.Hint: a*d > exp(Sigma)*b*c

BoxLocalization.Label: Fisher Quantifier
BoxLocalization.Hint: The one-sided Fisher test rejects on the level alpha the null hypothesis of independence of A and S in favour of the alternative of their positive logarithmic interaction.

BoxLocalization.Label: Chi-Squared Quantifier
BoxLocalization.Hint: The one-sided Fisher test asymptotically rejects on the level alpha the null hypothesis of independence of A and S in favour of the alternative of their positive logarithmic interaction.
